CH. 16. The general argument of this chapter is as follows: ‘This catalogue of tyrannical executions grows tedious, and the Iack of spirit shown by the victims might incline the historian to pass contemptuously over any record of their death. Ι do not however avoid such record : these horrors were due to the wrath of Heaven, and the victims deserve pity not condemnation. The historian must record evil as well as good; here I have to describe not a single calamity suffered by the whole body of the state and capable of narration in a single passage, but one that was distributed over a multitude of persons who, owing to their distinguished position, require individual mention.'
